{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21294"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21294"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.4,0.43,0.02,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106295"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14167"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"6211"},{"type":"tags","id":"12893"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37081"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106295"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sharp chest pain that worsens when lying flat and improves when sitting forward. He had an ST-elevation myocardial infarction two weeks ago, which was treated with percutaneous coronary intervention. His medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, metoprolol, and ramipril. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a pericardial friction rub. Lung fields are clear on auscultation. Investigations reveal a C-reactive protein of 45 mg/L (0-5) and a normal troponin. An echocardiogram shows a small pericardial effusion with no evidence of tamponade. ECG results as attached.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment to add for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcutaneous low molecular weight heparin","Ibuprofen","Colchicine","Warfarin","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with Dressler\u0027s syndrome (post-myocardial infarction pericarditis), which typically occurs 1-6 weeks after a myocardial infarction. The diagnosis is supported by the characteristic positional chest pain, pericardial friction rub, fever, elevated inflammatory markers, ECG changes showing diffuse ST elevation and PR depression, and the small pericardial effusion on echocardiogram.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColchicine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment for this patient. Current evidence demonstrates that colchicine combined with NSAIDs achieves superior outcomes as compared to NSAIDs alone, including better remission and lower recurrence rates. Given that this patient is already taking aspirin for his recent myocardial infarction, colchicine would be the optimal addition to his existing anti-inflammatory regimen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective NSAID for pericarditis, but when used alone it is less effective than combination therapy with colchicine. Since the patient is already receiving aspirin as an anti-inflammatory therapy following his myocardial infarction, adding colchicine would provide superior outcomes compared to ibuprofen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous low molecular-weight heparin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate for this patient. Anticoagulation is not indicated for uncomplicated pericarditis and may increase the risk of haemorrhagic transformation of the pericardial effusion. There is no evidence of deep vein thrombosis or pulmonary embolism in this case that would warrant anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E, an oral anticoagulant, is not indicated for the treatment of pericarditis. Like heparin, it may increase the risk of haemorrhagic transformation of the pericardial effusion. Warfarin would be considered in cases of atrial fibrillation or mechanical valve replacement, which are not present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E (corticosteroids) would be reserved for cases of pericarditis that are refractory to NSAIDs, or in patients with contraindications to these medications. Corticosteroids are generally avoided as first-line therapy due to the associated complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of Dressler\u0027s syndrome also includes monitoring for complications such as cardiac tamponade, which would require urgent pericardiocentesis. In this case, the echocardiogram shows no evidence of tamponade, so conservative management with anti-inflammatory medication is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dressler\u0027s syndrome is an autoimmune pericarditis that typically occurs 1-6 weeks after myocardial infarction or cardiac surgery.","Colchicine combined with NSAIDs achieves superior outcomes as compared to NSAIDs alone.","Positional chest pain that worsens with lying flat and improves with sitting forward is characteristic of pericarditis."],"references":["Sasse T, Eriksson U. Post-cardiac injury syndrome: aetiology, diagnosis, and treatment. e-Journal of Cardiology Practice. October 2017. Available from: https://www.escardio.org/Journals/E-Journal-of-Cardiology-Practice/Volume-15/Post-cardiac-injury-syndrome-aetiology-diagnosis-and-treatment","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Pericarditis. eTG Complete. 2025. Updated June, 2023. Accessed May 27, 2025. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21294"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21868"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21868"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0wGlZGHtzqwVbnrPqSbzmHjwHyxXCy.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0wGlZGHtzqwVbnrPqSbzmHjwHyxXCy.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":315}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T18:43:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T18:44:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14167"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106295"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":nu